{{short description|Saline woodland or shrubland habitat formed by mangrove trees}} [[File:Mangroves in Kannur, India.jpg|thumbnail|Mangroves in [[Kannur]], India.]]
A '''mangrove swamp''' was a distinct saline [[woodland]] or [[shrubland]] habitat formed by [[mangrove]] trees. They are characterized by [[Sedimentary depositional environment|depositional]] coastal environments, where fine sediments (often with high organic content) collect in areas protected from high-energy wave action. The saline conditions tolerated by various mangrove species range from [[brackish water]], through pure [[seawater]] (3 to 4%), to water concentrated by [[evaporation]] to over twice the [[salinity]] of ocean seawater (up to 9%).<ref name=NHMI>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhmi.org/mangroves/phy.htm |title=Morphological and Physiological Adaptations: Florida mangrove website |publisher=Nhmi.org |accessdate=2012-02-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204222702/http://www.nhmi.org/mangroves/phy.htm |archivedate=2012-02-04 |df= }}</ref> {{toclimit|3}}
==Birds sanctuaries==
Mangrove swamps are home and sanctuaries for thousands of [[aquatic bird]] species, including:
* [[Pulicat Lake Bird Sanctuary]] * [[Mangalavanam Bird Sanctuary]] * [[Salim Ali Bird Sanctuary]] * [[Pichavaram]] * [[Coringa Wildlife Sanctuary]] * [[Sundarbans National Park]]
==Natural coastal protection==
Mangrove swamps protect coastal areas from erosion, storm surge (especially during [[hurricanes]]), and tsunamis.<ref name="Mazda-2">{{cite journal | last1 = Mazda | first1 = Y. | last2 = Kobashi | first2 = D. | last3 = Okada | first3 = S. | year = 2005 | title = Tidal-Scale Hydrodynamics within Mangrove Swamps | url = | journal = Wetlands Ecology and Management | volume = 13 | issue = 6| pages = 647–655 | doi=10.1007/s11273-005-0613-4}}</ref><ref name="Danielsen">{{cite journal | last1 = Danielsen | first1 = F. | display-authors = etal | year = 2005 | title = The Asian tsunami: a protective role for coastal vegetation | url = | journal = Science | volume = 310 | issue = | page = 643 | doi=10.1126/science.1118387 | pmid=16254180}}</ref> The mangroves' massive root systems are efficient at dissipating wave energy.<ref name="Massel">{{cite journal | last1 = Massel | first1 = S. R. | last2 = Furukawa | first2 = K. | last3 = Brinkman | first3 = R. M. | year = 1999 | title = Surface wave propagation in mangrove forests | url = | journal = Fluid Dynamics Research | volume = 24 | issue = 4| pages = 219–249 | doi=10.1016/s0169-5983(98)00024-0| bibcode = 1999FlDyR..24..219M }}</ref> Likewise, they slow down tidal water enough so its sediment is deposited as the tide comes in, leaving all except fine particles when the tide ebbs.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mazda | first1 = Yoshihiro | display-authors = etal | year = 1997 | title = Drag force due to vegetation in mangrove swamps | url = | journal = Mangroves and Salt Marshes | volume = 1 | issue = | pages = 193–199 }}</ref> In this way, mangroves build their own environments.<ref name="Mazda-2" /> Because of the uniqueness of mangrove ecosystems and the protection against erosion they provide, they are often the object of conservation programs, including national [[Biodiversity Action Plan|biodiversity action plan]]s.<ref name="Danielsen" />
The protective value of mangrove swamps is sometimes overstated. Wave energy is typically low in areas where mangroves grow,<ref>Baird, Andrew (26 December 2006) "False Hopes and Natural Disasters" ''New York Times'' editorial</ref> so their effect on erosion can only be measured over long periods.<ref name="Massel" /> Their capacity to limit high-energy wave erosion is limited to events such as storm surges and tsunamis.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dahdouh-Guebas | first1 = F. | display-authors = etal | year = 2005 | title = How effective were mangroves as a defence against the recent tsunami? | url = | journal = Current Biology | volume = 15 | issue = 12| pages = 443–447 | doi=10.1016/j.cub.2005.06.008 | pmid=15964259}}</ref> Erosion often occurs on the outer sides of bends in river channels that wind through mangroves, while new stands of mangroves are appearing on the inner sides where sediment is [[Accretion (geology)|accruing]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2007}}
